[2] Russia (Lipetskaya Oblast)
Date: Fri 11 May 2012
Source: Gorodlip.ru [abridged & edited]
http://gorodlip.ru/events/e27758577/


Outbreak of measles in Lipetskaya Oblast reported
------------------------------------------
The Department of Health Administration of Lipetsk Oblast announced on 11 May 2012 that several cases of measles had been diagnosed in the Gryazi area. "Measles is a dangerous viral disease that has been absent in the Lipetsk region since the late 90s", the report stated. Protection from the disease can be achieved by vaccination. Doctors recommmend that inhabitants of the region shold attend their local clinic to be vaccinated. Children should be vaccinated in their 1st year, and at 6 years. Adults in the age range 18 to 35 who are uncertain of their vaccination status should also seek vaccination.

Measles is highly infectious and can probably be contracted by air-borne transmission perhaps even in the course of conversation with an infected individual. Complications as a result of measles virus infection can be very serious; including blindness, otitis media, and bronchopneumonia.

Measles can be contracted at any age in unvaccinated individuals. Symptoms 1st appear 7 to 14 days following exposure. The 1st symptoms are similar to those of the common cold -- fever, intoxication, inflammation of the mucous membranes of the upper respiratory tract. After 24 hours a characteristic body rash in the form of red spots develops. If there is the slightest suspicion of measles infection, medical attention should be sought immediately.

--
