[4] Venezuela (ex Lebanon)
Date: Mon 7 May 2012
Source: AVN (Agencia Venezolana de Noticias) [In Spanish, trans. & edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.avn.info.ve/node/111273


The Minister of Health denies existence of outbreak of measles in Venezuela
-------------------------------------------------
The Venezuelan Minister for Health, Eugenia Sader, stated that currently there is no outbreak of measles in the country, despite rumours to the contrary [See Measles update 2012 (19) 20120506.1124592, parts 4 & 5]. She explained that the person who traveled to Lebanon with his family developed a fever on the return flight, but no other symptoms. The Minster stated that: "This passenger had previously been in contact with a person who had measles."

The Minister observed that the Pan American Health Organisation had declared Venezuela free of measles and rubella as far back as 2007 on the basis of the program of free vaccination of the entire population, that contrasted with the situation then pertaining in some European countries.

Eugenia Sader stated that the febrile passenger had sought treatment at a private clinic where he was administered antibiotics and his clinical samples were sent to the National Institute of Hygiene for diagnostic testing. "A positive [measles diagnosis] was confirmed on 30 Apr 2012 and on 01 May 2012 the 160 people who had travelled on the same flight were contcted by the epidemiological surveillance team.

The Minister reiterated that there is no risk for the general population, since this is an imported case, not an indigenous case of measles. She recalled that last year in Venzuela 18 million people had been vaccinated.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail welcomes this clarification of previous confusing reports..It would seem, however, that the Venezuelan traveller who contracted measles in Lebanon was a person not covered by the nation's vaccination programme. - Mod.CP]
